{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5cb9250e-16d8-4112-8099-2c5df1b7b241","content":"## .NET 10+ Raised the x86-64 Baseline\n\nStarting with **.NET 10**, Microsoft raised the minimum x86-64 CPU baseline from **x86-64-v1** to **x86-64-v2**. .NET 11 inherits this requirement. The v2 baseline requires:\n\n- **SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2**\n- **POPCNT, CMPXCHG16B, LAHF/SAHF**\n\nYour 2012-era hardware likely has an **AMD Bulldozer** CPU, which lacks **SSE4.2** (added in Piledriver, late 2012), or a similarly aged processor missing one of these extensions.\n\n**Your other platforms are unaffected** — Arm64 (Windows Surface, Raspberry Pi 4) has its own baseline that hasn't changed in this way.\n\n### Options\n\n1. **Retire or replace** the old x86 node — simplest path.\n2. **Stay on .NET 10 (or earlier)** for workloads targeting that node, while upgrading the rest.\n3. **Check exactly what's missing** on the failing node:\n\n   ```bash\n   # On the failing Linux node:\n   grep -E 'sse4_2|ssse3|popcnt|cx16' /proc/cpuinfo | head -4\n   ```\n\n   Missing flags confirm which instructions the CPU lacks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"70442423-d187-4af3-a8cc-6fbd0ec9fc6b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements, so I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 10 (and continuing in .NET 11), Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. However, let me think more carefully...\n\n\nActually, I need to reconsider the timeline here. The shift to x86-64-v2 as the baseline was announced for .NET 10, requiring instruction sets like SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, LAHF/SAHF, and CMPXCHG16B. This is a breaking change that affects older hardware from around 2012 and earlier.\n\nLooking at when these instructions became available, Intel's Nehalem (2008) and later processors support x86-64-v2, while AMD's support is more complicated—Bulldozer came out in 2011, but some specific instructions like SSSE3 didn't arrive until later generations like Bobcat. So there are edge cases where 2012-era hardware might not have full x86-64-v2 support, particularly with certain AMD processors. Bulldozer (2011) had SSE4.1 but not SSE4.2—that came with Piledriver in 2012. So the issue is likely AMD hardware from around 2012 that's missing SSE4.2 or other x86-64-v2 requirements, though early Intel chips from that era like Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge would actually have full support.\n\nThe real answer is that .NET 10 bumped the baseline to x86-64-v2, and some 2012 AMD processors don't meet that requirement. The user needs to identify which specific instructions are missing and either upgrade the hardware or keep those nodes on .NET 9.","outputTokens":1473,"requestId":"E01B:3EF0C4:739913B:8055FD4:69F40682"},"id":"32ab9edf-4143-4e18-84c8-1b01215b29c8","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:49:22.539Z","parentId":"c849ba23-eacc-48e8-abfb-c093ba1ffe48"}
